{% for section in sections %}
## {{ loop.index }}. {{ section }}

{% if section == "Maintenance philosophy" %}
- Maintain early, document everything, and treat water, frost, fire, electrical, and terrace-edge risks as priority risks.
- Use monthly owner observations, seasonal readiness checks, annual professional reviews, and long-cycle renewal planning.
- Keep maintenance conservative because this cabin combines large glazing, timber/stone/glass facade interfaces, standing seam roofing, mountain climate exposure, terrace drainage, smart controls, and optional off-grid systems.
{% elif section == "Owner responsibilities" %}
- Keep the maintenance calendar current.
- Store manuals, warranties, certificates, photos, invoices, and inspection reports in the handover binder.
- Stop using unsafe systems and call licensed professionals when warning signs appear.
- Do not convert preliminary generated guidance into final manufacturer, trade, or authority instructions.
{% elif section == "5-year maintenance" %}
- Reassess exposed finishes, sealants, membranes, exterior fixings, gutters, roof accessories, terrace waterproofing, and system service history.
- Update the cost plan using contractor quotes; do not rely on placeholder prices.
{% elif section == "10-year maintenance" %}
- Review aging mechanical equipment, window and door hardware, facade coatings, exterior drainage, smart-home hardware, batteries, and generator reliability.
- Consider professional envelope and energy review before large renewal spending.
{% elif section == "20-year maintenance" %}
- Commission a condition survey for envelope, terrace, roof, structure interfaces, PV, battery, generator, HVAC, water, and wastewater systems.
- Plan major renewals before failure, especially where mountain weather limits emergency access.
{% elif section == "30-year renewal planning" %}
- Treat year 30 as a renewal-design checkpoint, not a routine checklist.
- Reconfirm legal requirements, codes, climate assumptions, energy strategy, insurance expectations, and owner use patterns.
